<DOC><DOCNO> AP880913-0037 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-09-13-88 0259EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r w PM-WashingtoninBrief     09-13 0351</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Washington in Brief,360</SECOND><HEAD>Postal Service Battling 2-Cent Stamp Scam</HEAD><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The Postal Service is cracking down on a scamby people who are selling mailers on the wrong information thatfirst-class letters can be mailed for just two cents.   The Postal Service has filed civil 370 complaints againstindividuals and companies in the last several months, mostlyhalting mail deliveries to those operating the scam.   Postal Inspector Billy Posey said Monday that the agency isprepared to file criminal charges in cases of repeat offenders.   Posey said that under the scam, potential buyers are told theycan cut mailing costs. Those responding are sent a copy of asection of the federal code that was repealed in 1970 which dealtwith business-reply mail, then available for two cents.</TEXT><HEAD>___</HEAD><HEAD>Meese Spokesman Announces Resignation</HEAD><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Patrick Korten, former Attorney General EdwinMeese III's spokesman for his last few months in office, is leavingthe Justice Department next week.   Korten will be replaced at Justice by Loye Miller, the directorof public affairs for the Department of Education under departingEducation Secretary William Bennett.   Korten, a staunch defender of Meese, said he will write at theHeritage Foundation, a conservative Washington think tank whereMeese now works, and hopes eventually to resume workingbroadcasting.</TEXT><HEAD>___</HEAD><HEAD>Congress Provides Money For Whooping Cranes</HEAD><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Legislation on its way to President Reaganwould have the government buy the last privately held land on aTexas island that is a wintering ground for the world's onlysurviving flock of whooping cranes that breeds in the wild.   The Interior Department appropriations bill, passed last week byCongress, provides $5.5 million for the purchase of 5,017 acres atthe southern tip of Matagorda Island, officials say.   The purchase will be the government's third and finalacquisition from the Texas Nature Conservancy, bringing the federalproperty on the Gulf Coast barrier island to 11,502 acres.   Because of growing flocks, the whooping cranes have had tosearch for new wintering grounds away from their traditional winterhome on nearby Aransas National Wildlife Refuge.</TEXT></DOC>